<node id="SKIN">
  <data key="d0">EVENT</data>
  <data key="d1">A visual inspection of the patient's skin condition showing no abnormalities.&lt;SEP&gt;Assessment of skin condition, revealing no rashes or lesions in this instance.&lt;SEP&gt;Cyanosis present on the skin indicates a lack of oxygenated blood in the tissues, suggesting potential issues with circulation or perfusion.&lt;SEP&gt;Examined for rashes, lesions, and overall condition.&lt;SEP&gt;No abnormalities were observed in the skin examination during the physical assessment.&lt;SEP&gt;No abnormalities were observed in the skin examination.&lt;SEP&gt;Normal color, warm and dry condition of the patient's skin.&lt;SEP&gt;Normal skin appearance for the individual's age, without any lesions or rashes.&lt;SEP&gt;Patient's skin is warm and moist, indicating good circulation.&lt;SEP&gt;Redness and swelling over mastoid area indicates a localized skin issue.&lt;SEP&gt;The examination of the skin for any abnormalities or signs of rashes.&lt;SEP&gt;The examination of the skin surface for any signs of rashes or lesions that could indicate dermatological conditions.&lt;SEP&gt;The outer covering of the body which is smooth, moist and pink.&lt;SEP&gt;The skin appears pale, cold, slightly cyanotic, indicating possible impaired blood circulation.&lt;SEP&gt;The skin is a vital organ involved in various physiological processes such as sensation, thermoregulation, and protection.&lt;SEP&gt;The skin is a vital part of the body's outer covering, serving as a protective layer against environmental damage and infections. It also plays a role in temperature regulation through sweating and blood vessels constricting or dilating.&lt;SEP&gt;The skin is checked for rashes or lesions.&lt;SEP&gt;The skin is described as coarse and pigmented during the systematic examination.&lt;SEP&gt;The skin is described as having no rash and appearing pale.&lt;SEP&gt;The skin is described as pale with no rashes or lesions.&lt;SEP&gt;The skin is described as warm and moist with no rashes.&lt;SEP&gt;The skin is the largest organ in the body, serving functions such as protection against pathogens, regulation of temperature, and sensation.&lt;SEP&gt;The skin is the outer covering of the body and can indicate various conditions based on rashes, lesions, or other abnormalities.&lt;SEP&gt;The skin is the outer covering of the body that protects against environmental damage and pathogens.&lt;SEP&gt;The skin over the left femur is described as warm, red, and swollen.&lt;SEP&gt;The skin was assessed as normal with no lesions or abnormalities.&lt;SEP&gt;The skin was examined for any rashes or lesions.</data>
