  <data key="d1">Assessed for size, symmetry, and presence of lymphadenopathy.&lt;SEP&gt;Evaluation of the neck region for any masses, tenderness, or other concerning findings related to lymphatic system health.&lt;SEP&gt;Goiter present with an enlarged and tender thyroid gland.&lt;SEP&gt;Inspecting the neck for masses or other signs of pathology.&lt;SEP&gt;No goiter or jugular venous distention were observed.&lt;SEP&gt;No significant lymphadenopathy in the neck; thyroid gland is not enlarged.&lt;SEP&gt;No thyromegaly, no jugular venous distention.&lt;SEP&gt;Normal range of motion and absence of masses were reported for this region.&lt;SEP&gt;Normal range of motion, no masses noted during systematic examination.&lt;SEP&gt;Supple neck with no masses or bruit observed.&lt;SEP&gt;Supple neck with no masses or bruit observed."&lt;SEP&gt;Supple without any sign of thyromegaly.&lt;SEP&gt;Supple without masses suggests that the patient's neck muscles are functioning normally and there are no visible tumors or masses present in the cervical region.&lt;SEP&gt;Supple, no masses&lt;SEP&gt;The neck area where swelling is observed on the left side and limited mobility due to a lump.&lt;SEP&gt;The neck includes muscles, bones (cervical vertebrae), lymph nodes, thyroid gland, and surrounding structures. Its suppleness and the absence of jugular venous distension are important indicators of health.&lt;SEP&gt;The neck is a region of the body that contains important structures like the thyroid gland, trachea, esophagus, and various nerves. It also provides mobility for the head.&lt;SEP&gt;The neck is a region of the body that contains several important structures including the thyroid gland, jugular veins, and cervical spine.&lt;SEP&gt;The neck is described as supple with no jugular vein distention.&lt;SEP&gt;The neck is described as supple with no masses or tenderness, indicating normal musculature and absence of underlying issues.&lt;SEP&gt;The neck is described as supple without any visible or palpable lymph node enlargement or distention of the jugular vein.&lt;SEP&gt;The neck is inspected for masses or thyroid enlargement.&lt;SEP&gt;The neck was assessed for jugular vein distention.&lt;SEP&gt;The neck was examined for range of motion, masses, tenderness; everything found to be within normal limits.&lt;SEP&gt;The patient's neck was supple with no signs of lymphadenopathy or swelling.&lt;SEP&gt;The upper part of the body extending from the head to the torso, containing muscles, nerves, blood vessels, and lymph nodes.</data>
